      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-01-19T18:14:46Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "My first pass at this was to do the cgroup directly from minijail.  However the sysfs interface required a lot of string and fs manipulation I wasn\u0027t comfortable adding to this codebase.\n\nAlso, sending a list of the various cgoups was cumbersome.  Specifying a path for cpu, cpuacct, devices, and freezer wasn\u0027t pretty.\n\nThe other option I considered was passing a list of FDs in to minijail, and have it write the pid to each of those, which was a little better but still didn\u0027t feel quite right.",
      "parentUuid": "274e5eac_c32136de",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 9,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 13,
        "endChar": 8
      },
      "revId": "0406f02920424901b9471f25967624a5069ce8d9",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "07495aa4_7c94436d",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 13,
      "author": {
        "id": 1076138
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-01-19T19:05:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "That\u0027s a good point.\n\nI think what worries me about this mechanism is that it would allow you to (accidentally) undo or change the restrictions already added by Minijail. Granted, a lot of the priv-dropping operations would prevent you from gaining any privilege, but it still feels weird to have a bunch of things that can be configured (in a \"data-only\" way), and then just a callback function.\n\nOne option would be to always set no_new_privs when we\u0027re gonna use a callback, but this might not work in the Android case since things launched from init need capabilities and such.",
      "parentUuid": "87562a44_38ff7380",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 9,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 13,
        "endChar": 8
      },
      "revId": "0406f02920424901b9471f25967624a5069ce8d9",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c75ca266_fc04cf60",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 13,
      "author": {
        "id": 1067948
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-01-19T19:24:30Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The callback does give the API user an opportunity to screw things up.  Maybe it\u0027s not that bad because it\u0027s after the fork.  The callback would have to be pretty explicit about affecting the child process, and it could do the same things after minijail_run returns I guess.\n\nI could also piggy-back this on pid_file, since it has the exact same semantics.  Passing the list of cgroup/tasks paths is a little awkward, but fits the current config model better.  What do you think?\n\nThanks!",
      "parentUuid": "07495aa4_7c94436d",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 9,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 13,
        "endChar": 8
      },
      "revId": "0406f02920424901b9471f25967624a5069ce8d9",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "87562a44_23ed88ab",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 13,
      "author": {
        "id": 1076138
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-01-19T21:19:25Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The difference is that after minijail_run is done and the sandboxed program gets control when its main() routine is called, all sandboxing has taken place. On the other hand, after fork but before exec, there\u0027s sandboxing calls that haven\u0027t happened (because they happen in the preload code).\n\nIf you only need to write a pid to a file, the pid_file mechanism could be generalized. I\u0027m worried that the semantics in that case will not be clear (\"add to cgroup\" vs \"write to a file\"). That can probably be solved by exposing the API with the right names.\n\nI\u0027m not sure it makes sense to pass fds to libminijail. A list of files doesn\u0027t seem like a terrible idea, nor would a file with one filename per line. What do you think? How many cgroup files are we talking about?\n\nRealistically, you\u0027ve though about this in the context of consuming this API so you might have the most context on what is the best way to do it. I\u0027m not super worried about the callback but I think it\u0027s always a good goal to keep Minijail as \"data-driven\" as possible.",
      "parentUuid": "c75ca266_fc04cf60",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 9,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 13,
        "endChar": 8
      },
      "revId": "0406f02920424901b9471f25967624a5069ce8d9",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
